# Predicates:
Season(x) ::: x is a season.
Spring() ::: The season is Spring.
Summer() ::: The season is Summer.
Fall() ::: The season is Fall.
Winter() ::: The season is Winter.
Student(x) ::: x is a student.
WantsLongVacation(x) ::: x wants to have a long vacation.
Loves(x, y) ::: x loves y.
FavoriteSeason(x, y) ::: y is the favorite season of x.
Year() ::: There is a year.
HasSeason(x, y) ::: The year x has the season y.

# Premises:
# Define the seasons as distinct constants.
spring, summer, fall, winter

# Predicate defining what constitutes a season.
# This ensures that only these four are considered seasons.
Season(s) ::: s is a season.
∀s (Season(s) ↔ (s = spring ∨ s = summer ∨ s = fall ∨ s = winter))

# Define individuals as students.
Student(emma)
Student(mia)
Student(james)

# Define favorite seasons.
# Emma's favorite season is summer.
FavoriteSeason(emma, summer)
# And only summer.
∀s (FavoriteSeason(emma, s) → s = summer)

# Mia's favorite season is not Emma's favorite season.
# We need to declare that Mia has a favorite season.
FavoriteSeason(mia, mia_fav)
# And that this favorite season is not summer.
mia_fav ≠ summer

# Define desires for long vacations.
# James wants a long vacation.
WantsLongVacation(james)

# Rule: All students who want a long vacation love summer.
# This implies if a student has a long vacation desire, they must love summer.
∀x (Student(x) ∧ WantsLongVacation(x) → Loves(x, summer))

# Define the year and its seasons.
# Assume a single year entity.
Year(the_year)
# Assert that the year has these specific seasons.
HasSeason(the_year, spring)
HasSeason(the_year, summer)
HasSeason(the_year, fall)
HasSeason(the_year, winter)
# Ensure no other seasons are present in the year.
∀s (HasSeason(the_year, s) → (s = spring ∨ s = summer ∨ s = fall ∨ s = winter))

# Additional premises for completeness and to avoid implicit assumptions:
# Ensure seasons are distinct constants.
spring ≠ summer ∧ spring ≠ fall ∧ spring ≠ winter ∧ summer ≠ fall ∧ summer ≠ winter ∧ fall ≠ winter

# It is assumed that each student has exactly one favorite season.
∀x, s1, s2 (FavoriteSeason(x, s1) ∧ FavoriteSeason(x, s2) → s1 = s2)

# Conclusion:
FavoriteSeason(james, fall)

# Predicates:

Fall() ::: The season is Fall.
Winter() ::: The season is Winter.
Student(x) ::: x is a student.
WantsLongVacation(x) ::: x wants to have a long vacation.
Loves(x, y) ::: x loves y.

Year() ::: There is a year.

# Premises:
# Define the seasons
Season(spring).
Season(summer).
Season(fall).
Season(winter).

# All seasons are distinct
distinct(spring, summer).
distinct(spring, fall).
distinct(spring, winter).
distinct(summer, fall).
distinct(summer, winter).
distinct(fall, winter).

# The set of all seasons
∀s (Season(s) ↔ (s = spring ∨ s = summer ∨ s = fall ∨ s = winter)).

# Students who want a long vacation love summer the most.
# This means if a student wants a long vacation, they love summer.
# It does not imply that they love ONLY summer.
∀x (Student(x) ∧ WantsLongVacation(x) → Loves(x, summer)).

# Emma's favorite season is summer.
FavoriteSeason(emma, summer).

# Mia's favorite season is not the same as Emma's.
# This implies Mia has a favorite season.
# And her favorite season is different from Emma's favorite season.
∃s_mia (FavoriteSeason(mia, s_mia) ∧ s_mia ≠ summer).

# James wants to have a long vacation.
WantsLongVacation(james).

# Identify students.
Student(emma).
Student(mia).
Student(james).

# The year has all four seasons.
Year(the_year).
HasSeason(the_year, spring).
HasSeason(the_year, summer).
HasSeason(the_year, fall).
HasSeason(the_year, winter).

# All students who want a long vacation love summer the most.
# This is a rephrasing of the original, ensuring clarity.
∀x (Student(x) ∧ WantsLongVacation(x) → Loves(x, summer)).

# Emma is a student.
Student(emma).

# Mia is a student.
Student(mia).

# James is a student.
Student(james).

# The favorite season is a unique season for a student.
# This is an implicit assumption that is good to make explicit if needed,
# but the original prompt implies this by using FavoriteSeason(x, y).
# If we wanted to be extremely explicit:
# ∀x ∃!s FavoriteSeason(x, s).
# However, the existing premise `∃s_mia (FavoriteSeason(mia, s_mia) ∧ s_mia ≠ summer)`
# already implies that Mia has at least one favorite season, and it's not summer.
# The premise `FavoriteSeason(emma, summer)` also implies Emma has a favorite season.
# We will assume FavoriteSeason implies uniqueness for simplicity and consistency with the original.

# Conclusion:
FavoriteSeason(james, fall)
